{"type":"message","id":"716ca521","parentId":"29fa51fc","timestamp":"2026-04-06T00:59:08.302Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see. The 55.07% strategy is \"Qlib breadth + turnover hardcap relaxed\" - this is the stable strategy audit that shows 55.07% annualized return with 2.794 Sharpe and 24.89% drawdown.\n\nNow the user is asking: \"Why are we still using the 55% strategy as baseline when there's already a higher return strategy?\" \n\nLooking at the backtest results:\n- smallcap_walk_forward_aggressive_20260314: 年化 25.60%，Sharpe 1.625，回撤 8.13%\n\n\n- Qlib breadth + turnover hardcap relaxed: 年化 55.07%，Sharpe 2.794，回撤 24.89%\n\nActually, 55.07% is the highest return I'm seeing in these results. Let me reconsider the user's concern - they mentioned a \"higher return strategy\" exists. Looking at the backtest queue status more carefully, I need to check if there's another strategy with even better performance that I'm missing.\n\nThe smallcap_walk_forward_aggressive shows lower returns at 25.60%, while the HS300 XGBoost strategy from the other workspace shows around 42.9% annualized returns. So the Qlib breadth + turnover hardcap relaxed strategy at 55.07% actually appears to be the best performer across all these options.\n\nBut the user is suggesting there's a higher-return strategy already in place, so I should look deeper into the audit logs and daily strategy files to see if there's something I'm overlooking.","thinkingSignature":"becb6cec06928e3c25d2882a976cf8927b0d1d556d6b6374b48c0c7ff945f0db"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_blembr3va0my_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace -name \"*audit*\" -o -name \"*strategy_audit*\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modules | head -10; echo \"---\"; find /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace -name \"daily_strategy_audit*\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modules | head -10"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_blembr3va0my_2","name":"exec",