{"type":"message","id":"456a6793","parentId":"277b318d","timestamp":"2026-04-06T05:40:55.418Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The index CSV doesn't exist. So the trading day check in `auto_run_premarket_precheck.py` falls back to the weekday check. \n\nFor a more complete solution, I should hardcode the major Chinese public holidays. But that's fragile. \n\nActually, the simplest pragmatic fix for `run_investment_research_background_cycle.py` is to:1. Check if today is weekend (already done)\n2. Check if there's a newer trading day data available - if the last data date is more than 1 day ago and today is Monday-Friday, it might be a holiday\n\nBut this is getting complicated. Let me think about what the user really needs:\n\n\nThe user is pointing out that the \"临时会商监控\" and \"警戒观察\" mechanisms should only run on trading days, not holidays. Today is 清明节 (Qingming Festival), which is a public holiday in China, so the system shouldn't be triggering these alerts at all. This is really about the cron schedule needing to account for Chinese public holidays rather than just weekdays.\n\nThe core issue is that using `1-5` in cron expressions doesn't capture holidays like 清明节, National Day, or other Chinese public holidays. I could hardcode a Python function to check for major 2026 holidays, but that's not maintainable. A better approach would be to pull the actual trading calendar from an API like Baidu or Sina, or check the Tushare data if it's available in the workspace.","thinkingSignature":"22a955ebf8576fa0eb08aca2e07451ddf42bc6783ec5ab0306648912dffe7dbf"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4cyx98vn7dz9_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace -name \"*tushare*\" -o -name \"*calendar*\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modules | grep -v \".pyc\" | head -10; echo \"---\"; ls /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/scripts/ | grep -i \"trade\\|cal\\|holiday\\|tushare\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-m