{"type":"message","id":"ab9ba3a1","parentId":"20bfb3e0","timestamp":"2026-04-06T10:55:56.502Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The latest window (2026-01-12 ~ 2026-03-03) shows Sharpe=0.000 and annual=0.00%. This is a very short window (less than 2 months), and it seems like it ended on March 3rd (which is the last data in the Qlib calendar). This is because the walk-forward data only goes up to 2026-03-03. The latest window in the walk-forward might be very short (only ~2 months) and might not have enough data to compute meaningful metrics.\n\nLooking at the `aggressive_walkforward_summary_20260404_210104.json` - this seems to be a different run from the main one we registered. Let me check which one the script picked.\n\n\nThe script used the most recently modified file rather than the official one, and that latest file shows zero returns for the final window, which makes sense given it only spans from early January to early March.\n\nThe actual 9-window summary with 58.48% returns was generated earlier on April 4th at 20:18:11, but the modification times suggest the later run at 21:01:04 is more recent. I should verify which one has the actual comprehensive results versus which might be a partial or interim run.\n\nWait, both windows files were created on the same day with timestamps only 43 minutes apart, so the second run was likely just a continuation or refinement. The real issue is that the latest window data only extends through March 3rd, which is the last available trading date, so if today is April 6th, we're missing almost a month of data. But here's what's striking: all the metrics for this window—Sharpe ratio, annual returns, maximum drawdown—are showing as exactly zero, which suggests something went wrong with the calculation or data extraction for that final window.\n\nLooking at the window definitions, the 9th window should run from January 9th to July 8th, 2026 based on the standard walk-forward methodology with 6-month test periods. But the actual end date is March 3rd, which is much shorter than expected. This could mean the backtester only had data through early March, or the last window was treated as incomplete and excluded from calculations. I need to check the actual aggressive walk-forward summary file to understand why the metrics are zero and what the real date range is. Looking at the date arithmetic, a January 12th start with a 3-month offset should land around July 12th, not March 3rd—so something's off with how the end date was calculated or the window definition itself.\n\nThe zero metrics are puzzling though. If the walk-forward was run with data through early March 2026 and today is April 6th, there's a data cutoff issue. But more concerning is that both the Sharpe ratio and returns are exactly zero, which suggests either the window had insufficient data points, was explicitly excluded from calculations, or the backtest completely failed for that period.\n\nI need to check the actual JSON file to see what went wrong with window 9.","thinkingSignature":"a6772478c14736ef4f376091a12a4de2968d205624aad9e64f033f837fbe718e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2hi80z2skr3b_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"python3 -c \"\nimport json\nd = json.load(open('/Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/aggressive_walkforward_summary_20260404_210104.json'))\nwindows = d.get('windows', [])\nprint(f'窗口数: {len(windows)}')\nfor w in windows:\n    print(f'  window {w[\\\"window_id\\\"]}: test={w[\\\"test_start\\\"]}~{w[\\\"test_end\\\"]}, sharpe={w.get(\\\"test_sharpe_daily\\\",\\\"?\\\")}, ann={w.get(\\\"test_annual_pct\\\",\\\"?\\\")}, mdd={w.get(\\\"test_mdd_pct\\\",\\\"?\\\")}')\n\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":103258,"output":821,"cacheRead":21467,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125546,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead"