{"type":"message","id":"f5a46db6","parentId":"5b4ad5c7","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:33:28.559Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Both accounts fail with the same \"open_id cross app\" error. This means the user `ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` was created by a different Feishu app, not these three.\n\nBut wait - the messages ARE coming through to this user through OpenClaw. How is OpenClaw sending messages if the open_id doesn't work? Let me check the inbound metadata - it shows `sender_id: ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae`. So OpenClaw is definitely receiving messages from this user, but how is it sending?\n \nAh, I see it now - the message comes through the Feishu channel and OpenClaw replies on the same channel using the message_id, so there's no need for a separate API call to send. The incoming message has a reply_to_id that OpenClaw uses to respond directly.\n\nBut if I want to proactively send messages to this user, I'd need to use the Feishu API with the correct credentials and reply_id. I'm wondering if there's a chat_id already established in the session data that I could use instead of trying to look up the user fresh.\n\nLooking at the message metadata, I see the sender_id and chat_id fields, but chat_id isn't what I need for the Feishu API - I'd need the user's open_id from their actual Feishu account, and I'm not certain which app was used to authorize this user in the first place.\n\nSince all three accounts are returning the same \"open_id cross app\" error, I'm thinking the issue might be that these are custom apps created in Feishu's ecosystem rather than the standard \"机器人\" bot type, which could mean they have different open_id generation rules or API permissions. Let me try using the chat_id directly in the Feishu API call instead, since I have that information available.\n\nLooking at the inbound metadata more carefully, I see `sender_id: ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` and `chat_id: user:ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` - this is a direct message chat, so the chat_id and sender_id are the same. The real issue is that OpenClaw's accounts are using one app, but this user's open_id was created through a different app, so they might not be compatible. The OpenClaw Feishu channel might be using websocket mode or a different API mechanism that handles this transparently.\n\nLet me try sending to the chat_id instead of the user open_id directly.","thinkingSignature":"be6d88b1eb209e821bdbc4a878d81cce820a5021632a4006520b49e770a26b89"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_qqrgm5tb53ml_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw message send --channel feishu --account feishu-assistant --target \"user:ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\" --message \"测试\" 2>&1 | tail -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":103366,"output":640,"cacheRead":21467,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":125473,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775475187248,"responseId":"0622ccf32246b82d4f9ac59eeef64de9"}}
