{"type":"message","id":"cdfa1224","parentId":"9dc72626","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:34:05.947Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I can't find the chat_id in the data files. Let me try a different approach - I'll look at how OpenClaw stores its channel state for feishu.Actually, let me try using `receive_id_type=chat_id` instead of `receive_id_type=open_id` with the chat_id that I know. Since the user and I are in a DM chat, the chat_id should be the same as the user's ID in Feishu's system.Wait, actually for DM chats, the chat_id IS the user's open_id (in Feishu's internal representation). But the issue is cross-app - the open_id was created by a different app.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach: use the Feishu API to get the user's open_id by their email or phone, using the app's credentials. Or better yet, let me check if the Feishu app has the ability to look up users.Actually, looking at the error again: \"open_id cross app\". This specifically means the open_id does NOT belong to the app being used. Each Feishu app has its own set of user IDs. \n\nThe `ou_` prefix is consistent across apps, but the underlying ID values differ - what I'm seeing is the unified ID from Feishu's identity system, not the app-specific one. For the API calls to work, I need the app-specific user ID that was created when this app was installed in the tenant. Let me try sending with the `receive_id_type` set to `union_id` instead, since the system metadata shows the sender's union ID as well.\n\nI should search the OpenClaw database directly for the correct user mapping.","thinkingSignature":"8177ec504a94005e4ad1d6a07ffd41be95a96119da67de79b2645c60daba954a"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_yzp83qp2i4q6_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"find ~/.openclaw/data -name \"*.db\" -o -name \"*.sqlite\" 2>/dev/null | head -5; echo \"---\"; find ~/.openclaw -name \"*.sqlite*\" -o -name \"channel_state*\" 2>/dev/null | grep -v node_modu