{"type":"message","id":"b9d8a703","parentId":"8d539e33","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:34:39.536Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"None of the sqlite files have user/channel data. The Feishu user data must be stored somewhere else, or it's managed by the Feishu plugin itself.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Instead of using the openclaw message CLI (which doesn't work cross-app), let me try to find if OpenClaw stores a session or chat_id that I can use.\n\nActually, thinking about this differently: OpenClaw's coding-agent is receiving messages from 张玲 through Feishu, and it REPLIES to them. How does it reply? It uses the `channel.reply_to` mechanism with the incoming message's ID. That works because the message_id is from the correct app.\n \nSo for proactive sends, I could use the same reply mechanism if I have a message_id from this chat. The current message has ID `om_x100b520dc53864a0c247cf6fd87dbe3`, but I can't reuse that since it's already been sent. I need to figure out how to send a new message without replying to an existing one.\n\nThe real issue is that all three Feishu app accounts show \"open_id cross app\" errors—this open_id clearly belongs to a different app. Since OpenClaw is already successfully delivering messages to this user, it must have access to a working bot token, but I can't locate it in the configuration files. Let me check the Gateway configuration instead.","thinkingSignature":"e947a7834e43848176bb887097087b4e3ae164026238ec67330aec67f5e121c8"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_jgwosucn835i_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat ~/.openclaw/openclaw.json | python3 -c \"import json,sys; d=json.load(sys.stdin); print(json.dumps({k:v for k,v in d.items() if 'feishu' in k.lower() or 'gateway' in k.lower() or 'plugin' in k.lower()}, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False))\" 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":102091