{"type":"message","id":"9884765b","parentId":"816a7a78","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:38:52.145Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The existing scripts use `target_user = \"user:ou_968a615509dc191f04220e18cda67080\"` - a different open_id! This is the key difference. The current `message send` is using `user:ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` (张玲), but the existing scripts use `user:ou_968a615509dc191f04220e18cda67080` - which might be a valid open_id for the same app that the main Feishu account can send to.\n\nBut wait - this is the same Feishu app (the openclaw channel). The `open_id cross app` error means the app is trying to send to an open_id that was created by a different app. If the main app (cli_a928c429d9785cc6) was installed by 张玲 in the same Feishu organization, then open_ids should be compatible...\n \nActually, I'm realizing the real issue: the Feishu bot can only message users who've both installed the same app AND authorized it. The `ou_968a615509dc191f04220e18cda67080` open_id likely belongs to a user who's installed the app, while `ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` might not have installed it - that's probably why the message is bouncing.\n\nBut here's the puzzle: I'm receiving messages in this conversation through OpenClaw, so the app clearly has some connection to my account. The issue is that OpenClaw's CLI command uses a different API endpoint than the SDK, and the CLI might not be routing through the same message path that the SDK uses for incoming messages.\n\nLet me reconsider - maybe the `openclaw message send` command works for some users but not others, or perhaps `ou_968a615509dc191f04220e18cda67080` is a chat_id instead of an open_id. Let me look back at what the user actually said about the configuration...\n\nThe user confirmed they already set up the webhook, which means the existing cron jobs are successfully pushing. If I check the message history, I can probably find what the other open_id