{"type":"message","id":"c086aff0","parentId":"2de68930","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:49:08.689Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is confirmed: all these app IDs (including the ones from openclaw.json) cannot send messages to `ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` because they were created under different apps and this open_id belongs to a different app context.\n\nThe only way to send to this open_id is through the app that owns it. But how does the `message` tool in my current session send to it? Let me look at the inbound metadata again.\n\nMy inbound metadata says:\n```json\n\"chat_id\": \"user:ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n\n\n```\n\nSo the current session IS receiving messages from and can reply to this open_id through the app that owns it. The key difference is that when I'm running in this session with the Feishu plugin enabled, I'm using the `messaging/...` methods rather than the raw SDK client.\n\nSo the real question is whether the cron job—which runs separately with its own isolated session context—has the same plugin bindings. The cron job itself is just a shell wrapper calling a Python script via `cron_python.sh`, so it doesn't inherently have access to the messaging plugin. That's probably why the subprocess command to send a message failed.\n\nBut here's the interesting part: if the cron job's shell wrapper itself was configured with the feishu plugin, then when it calls `openclaw message send`, it would actually be running within that plugin context and could potentially access the right credentials. Let me look back at the feishu config in openclaw.json to understand how the accounts are structured.\n\nLooking at the config, I can see the feishu-assistant account uses appId `cli_a9256a7ae9b91cb6`. The key insight is that the open_id `ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae` is associated with this particular app, not the main account. When I send a message through this session, I'm using that app's credentials through the feishu-assistant account. The cron job must be using a different account configuration, which is why it fails.\n\n```\nbut different plugin context\n```\n\nI'm wondering if there's a way to invoke the cron session's feishu plugin directly to send the message, since the Python script runs independently and the cron itself doesn't have a direct way to access the plugin. The key question is whether I can configure the cron wrapper to use the feishu-assistant account specifically when calling `openclaw message send`. Looking at the command the user configured, they might have already set up the target user with the right account credentials.\n\nI'm noticing the command doesn't specify `--account`, but the feishu plugin likely resolves the user based on the current session context. I could try using `--account feishu-assistant` or the `feishu-assistant` app ID to see if that makes a difference.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the cron session is probably using the \"coding-agent\" account (from the runtime config showing `account_id: \"coding-agent\"`), which is `cli_a934da0dde385cba` — not the feishu-assistant account. That's likely why it's failing. Let me test with `--account feishu-assistant` directly.","thinkingSignature":"701250af1a19136f5f8d0348722b823c10935d4fc0252e3dd373c8e05f187f5e"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_aij26z0guizd_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw message send --channel feishu --account feishu-assistant --target \"user:ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\" --message \"🔴 测试：这条应该能收到\" 2>&1 | tail -3"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":109098,"output":782,"cacheRead":21467,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131347,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775476126557,"responseId":"0622d09e8dfd7897d8e8842f8de4e7b3"}}
