{"type":"message","id":"15d13575","parentId":"34f397aa","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:52:58.077Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK! So the OpenClaw cron system manages all these jobs, and they're stored in OpenClaw's own database, not in the system crontab. The `crontab -l` that showed entries earlier were probably from the OpenClaw cron system, not the system crontab.\n\nSo when I ran `crontab -l | grep -v \"...\" | crontab -`, I was removing from the SYSTEM crontab, not the OpenClaw cron. The system crontab was probably always empty, and what I was seeing was the OpenClaw cron list output.\n\nActually wait - looking at the OpenClaw cron list, those all have IDs, not command strings. \n\nBut when I ran `crontab -l` earlier, I saw actual shell commands with specific paths and file redirections, not the structured format OpenClaw uses. So there were definitely two separate systems at play here.\n\nLooking at what was actually in the system crontab, I can see several commands pointing to scripts in the quant_projects directory - things like the paper profiles rebuild, the quantitative panels at 16:10, the conservative shadow cron, the workout reminder, and some other task running a shadowrocket node sync script.\n\nWait, I think I see what happened. When I ran `crontab -l` and piped it through grep to filter out the auto audit entry, the issue might be that the crontab was stored in a format that didn't have a trailing newline. When grep removes a line, the next `echo` command might have concatenated everything together, breaking the format. Let me just check what's actually in the crontab now to confirm it's empty.","thinkingSignature":"b095155ef1682c39b59a990b8e2105979161dd814a6a8b359ae456aed68e178d"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_781uac4dm7rp_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"crontab -l 2>&1; echo \"exit: $?\""}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":107