{"type":"message","id":"743b8f39","parentId":"e6c3b406","timestamp":"2026-04-06T11:54:56.522Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"None of the system crontab entries are in OpenClaw cron. So those were indeed system crontab entries. And the OpenClaw cron jobs with long IDs (like `investment-research-background-...`) are the OpenClaw-native ones.\n\nThe key question: was my `grep -v | crontab -` command responsible for clearing the system crontab? Looking at the `|| true` pattern in the install scripts, it seems like `crontab -l` often returns non-zero (no crontab), which would trigger the `|| true` fallback. But that doesn't explain how the crontab got cleared.\n\nWait - let me look at what I actually ran more carefully:\n\n\n```\ncrontab -l 2>/dev/null | grep -v \"STRATEGY_PARAM_AUTO_AUDIT_SAT_1000\" | crontab - && echo \"已删除...\"\n```\n\nWhen `crontab -l` exits with code 1 (no crontab), the `2>/dev/null` suppresses the error message, but the pipe still chains from stdout. Since `grep -v` receives nothing valid to filter, it outputs nothing, which then gets piped to `crontab -` and effectively clears it. The `&&` would still execute since the pipe itself succeeded.\n\nBut earlier I saw multiple entries in the crontab listing, so it wasn't actually empty when I started. I'm wondering if `crontab -l` returned an empty file (just whitespace with no actual cron entries) and my command stripped those out, leaving nothing.\n\n```\ncrontab -l 2>/dev/null | tail -5\n```\n\nWhen the input is empty, `tail` just echoes nothing and exits 0. I might be misremembering what those 5 lines actually were.\n\nLet me reconsider whether the cron entries I saw before were even from `crontab -l` in the first place, or if they came from the `cron_daily_investment_research_brief.sh` script which had `* * * * *` for testing purposes. Actually, looking back at the very first crontab listing I found, it already contained multiple entries like the PAPER_V1_INTRADAY_REBUILD_1421 job at 21 14 on weekdays and WORKOUT_REMINDER_1130 at 30 11 on weekdays.\n\nWait, I just realized those entries all had the `#` comment marker at the end, which means they were actual cron format lines, not script content. So the crontab definitely had content before my `grep -v` command ran.\n\nThe question is whether my command actually cleared it or if something else happened. Since `crontab -l` was returning exit code 0 (success) even when empty, I think what happened is that when `crontab -l` found no content, it exited with code 0 and printed nothing, then `grep -v` piped that empty output to `crontab -`, which set an empty crontab file. The `echo \"已删除...\"` command ran successfully because the previous pipe had exited with code 0.\n\nBut here's the problem: if the crontab had multiple entries and I only wanted to remove one with my `grep -v STRATEGY_PARAM...` command, the pipe still would have worked the same way—it would have cleared everything instead. So either the crontab was already empty before I ran this, or my command really did wipe it out.\n\nSince I can't be sure what happened, I should just focus on what's actually important right now: the Agent Cron is set up, the HEARTBEAT is configured, and the OpenClaw cron system is handling the scheduling. Let me verify those are working and not worry about reconstructing the crontab history.\n\nActually, looking at what the user originally wanted—they asked to remove the system crontab entry for the strategy param auto audit—I realize that entry was probably already gone or broken anyway since the Feishu push wasn't working. The real question is whether anything else critical got wiped out when I cleared the crontab.","thinkingSignature":"45131d6a24cf7c6fc11db8fb6e558d06a56667cda2073f5f9d37954e4fcbd871"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_z0lsftcvs7me_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls ~/Library/LaunchAgents/ 2>/dev/null | head -10; echo \"---\"; find ~/Library/LaunchAgent