{"type":"message","id":"d8928b8a","parentId":"bdae8ea7","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:08:34.718Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking \"这个任务做完了么？\" (Is this task done?) in a Feishu group chat (chatId: oc_678d42a0a24a843972ef716cf508deb9). They're replying to an interactive card.\n\nThe chat_id is a group chat (oc_ prefix), not the direct chat. The replied-to message is an interactive card. I still can't read the interactive card content.\n\nThe question \"这个任务做完了么？\" seems to be about some task. Given the context of our conversation, it could be:\n1. The strategy parameter audit setup we just worked on\n2. Something from the group chat\n\nThe replied-to message is \"[Interactive Card]\" which I can't read. \n\nWithout being able to see what the interactive card actually says, I'm not sure which task they're asking about. I could ask for clarification, but let me think about what makes sense given the timing—our conversation was about the strategy parameter audit and the paper trading profile update, and the agent cron is set for Saturday at 10am.\n\nThe user might be referencing something from the group chat itself rather than our direct conversation, or they could be asking about the full context of what we discussed. I should probably just ask them directly which specific task they're referring to since I can't read the card.","thinkingSignature":"aba42675e606581d8d70c1212d82d538e004962d61bdb3816cf54af78b38ab54"},{"type":"text","text":"卡片内容我还是看不到 😅 是指哪个任务？\n\n能截图发给我，或者把卡片内容复制成文字吗？"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":105007,"output":296,"cacheRead":21467,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":126770,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775477302450,"responseId":"0622d53663d79d403413fc6bb06bfc4b"}}
{"type":"message","id":"20f0fd37","parentId":"d8928b8a","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:09:22.924Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b520e69de34a4c4ab69213bd9f65\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"sender\": \"张玲\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-04-06 20:09 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"张玲 (ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"name\": \"张玲\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b520e69de34a4c4ab69213bd9f65]\n张玲: 为什么你自己发的消息你还看不到？"}],"timestamp":1775477362919}}
{"type":"message","id":"e6e7bfaa","parentId":"20f0fd37","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:09:37.087Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking why I can't see messages that I sent myself. This is a good question. The issue is that when I use the `message` tool to send a message, I'm sending it FROM the bot TO the user. The message_id in the inbound context refers to the user's message to me, not my message to them. So the `read` action is trying to read a message that was sent TO me, not a message I sent.\n\nActually, the issue might be simpler - when the user sends a message that contains an Interactive Card (which is a rich card message), that card has content that I can't read because it's rendered differently. The card content is shown as \"[Interactive Card]\" in the inbound message body.\n \nI'm realizing the distinction here: the inbound message is the user asking me something, but the card they're referring to is a message I previously sent them, not one I received. The reply_to_id points to their message asking \"这个任务做完了么？\", so they're asking me to check on something I sent earlier. 飞书的自定义卡片可能需要额外的权限或特殊处理才能读取内容。我应该直接问用户卡片里具体写了什么，而不是继续尝试解析。","thinkingSignature":"d40e3f4f933e0fb8667e38085d219ed2d284cab945ba75feee3e95cc286faa7e"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 好问题——确实是我发的消息，但从飞书 API 读回来的格式里，卡片里的具体内容显示为 `[Interactive Card]`，只是一个占位符，不是完整文本。\n\n这可能是飞书对 Interactive Card 的限制，读取回来的只有元数据（卡片ID、类型），没有卡片的实际文案内容。\n\n你能把卡片里的内容手打给我吗？或者截图发过来也行——这样我就能知道你在问哪个任务了。"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":343,"cacheRead":126666,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":127009,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775477362922,"responseId":"0622d57318cf011c13edfa1b1d18982f"}}
{"type":"message","id":"78e173ce","parentId":"e6e7bfaa","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:25:03.685Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b520e2f2daca4c4592c84f4b750f\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"sender\": \"张玲\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-04-06 20:25 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"张玲 (ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"name\": \"张玲\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b520e2f2daca4c4592c84f4b750f]\n张玲: 找到了，是 Karpathy 的 autoresearch 项目，不是知识库——是他在 GitHub 上新开源的一个 AI Agent 自动化科研框架。\n一句话总结：给 AI 一个真实可跑的小型 LLM 训练环境，AI 自己改代码、跑实验、看结果、决定是保留还是丢弃，然后循环——全自动、24小时不停、零人类干预。\n项目信息：\n- GitHub: https://github.com/karpathy/autoresearch\n- Stars: 66.5k（现在应该更多）\n- 代码量: 仅 630 行 Python\n- 依赖: 单张 GPU、Python 3.10+、uv 包管理工具\n核心三个文件：\n-  — 数据准备、工具函数\n-  — Agent 唯一会修改的训练主程序\n-  — 人类用自然语言写的研究目标，Agent 照着执行\n实验结果（Karpathy 自己跑出来的）：\n- 跑了 276 次实验，筛出 29 项有效改进\n- 48 小时内把 nanochat 模型的训练效率提升了约 11%\n- GPT-2 达标所需时间从 2.02 小时缩短到 1.8 小时\n最震撼的点：Karpathy 认为当前的 GitHub 设计（所有分支最终必须合并回 master）不适合 AI 高频探索。他想做的是：让成千上万个 AI Agent 在无数分支里异步协作，不再受单一 master 分支的限制——就像 SETI@home 那种分布式科研模式。\nREADME 里还专门提到了 OpenClaw（Clawdbot）——说它是一个\"开源 AI Agent，跑在本地机器上，通过 Telegram 等消息应用连接，完成研究、邮件分类、文件管理、网页浏览、部署等任务\"。算是点名认可了。\n我需要你更好的用这个skill"}],"timestamp":1775478303679}}
{"type":"message","id":"ec563255","parentId":"78e173ce","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:25:21.475Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking me to better utilize this Autoresearch skill. They previously shared this project and I explained it to them. Now they want me to actually integrate it or use it to improve their investment research system.\n\nLet me think about what makes sense here:\n\n1. Karpathy's autoresearch is about AI training - letting an AI agent run experiments on training code, evaluate results, and iterate autonomously.\n\n2. For the user's investment research system, the analogy would be: let an AI agent run experiments on strategy parameters, evaluate results, and iterate.\n\n3. However, there are key differences:\n   - Autoresearch works on a well-defined objective (loss reduction in training)\n   - Trading strategies have a noisy, non-stationary objective (returns/sharpe)\n   - A-b testing in trading takes days/weeks per round vs minutes in training\n   \nThe most immediately useful approach would be to leverage this distributed AI collaboration concept for the user's existing research - letting agents asynchronously explore different strategy parameters and hypothesis paths rather than requiring everything to merge back to a single master branch.\n\nBut the concrete first step is getting the weekly strategy parameter audit running properly, which we just finished setting up. I should focus on that and ask what specific aspect of the research system they want to apply this to.","thinkingSignature":"01e5bfca1c9abd059a73d4adcb3ae8443d1279dbf8f56aa599b28d962b9bdcad"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 好问题。让我先认真看一下 autoresearch 的代码，理解它的核心设计，再想怎么用到你的投研系统上。\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_n4f95ybdzvch_1","name":"tavily_extract","arguments":{"urls":["https://github.com/karpathy/autoresearch"],"query":"autoresearch karpathy how it works agent experiment loop structure","chunks_per_source":3}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":74,"output":364,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":127268,"totalTokens":127706,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775478303684,"responseId":"0622d920ba29666cefc190ffdba7ee90"}}
{"type":"message","id":"5eebbd6c","parentId":"ec563255","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:25:22.867Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_n4f95ybdzvch_1","toolName":"tavily_extract","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n  \"count\": 1,\n  \"tookMs\": 1365,\n  \"externalContent\": {\n    \"untrusted\": true,\n    \"source\": \"web_fetch\",\n    \"provider\": \"tavily\",\n    \"wrapped\": true\n  },\n  \"results\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://github.com/karpathy/autoresearch\",\n      \"rawContent\": \"\\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"a43f90e401148d1f\\\">>>\\nSource: Web Fetch\\n---\\n## Project structure\\n\\n\\ntrain.py        — model, optimizer, training loop (agent modifies this)\\nprogram.md      — agent instructions\\npyproject.toml  — dependencies\\n```\\n\\n## Design choices\\n\\n. Second, this means that autoresearch will find the most optimal model for your platform in that time budget. The downside is that your runs (and results) become not comparable to other people running on other compute platforms.\\n   Self-contained. No external dependencies beyond PyTorch and a few small packages. No distributed training, no complex configs. One GPU, one file, one metric.\\n\\n## Platform support [...] If you are new to neural networks, this \\\"Dummy's Guide\\\" looks pretty good for a lot more context.\\n\\n## Quick start\\n\\n, Python 3.10+, uv.\\n\\nundefinedshell\\n# 1. Install uv project manager (if you don't already have it)\\ncurl -LsSf  | sh\\n\\n# 2. Install dependencies\\nuv sync\\n\\n# 3. Download data and train tokenizer (one-time, ~2 min)\\nuv run prepare.py\\n\\n# 4. Manually run a single training experiment (~5 min)\\nuv run train.py\\nundefined\\n\\nIf the above commands all work ok, your setup is working and you can go into autonomous research mode.\\n\\n## Running the agent\\n\\n, then you can prompt something like:\\n\\n```\\nHi have a look at program.md and let's kick off a new experiment! let's do the setup first.\\n```\\n\\nThe `program.md` file is essentially a super lightweight \\\"skill\\\".\\n\\n## Project structure [...] ## How it works\\n\\n, and runtime utilities (dataloader, evaluation). Not modified.\\n   `train.py` — the single file the agent edits. Contains the full GPT model, optimizer (Muon + AdamW), and training loop. Everything is fair game: architecture, hyperparameters, optimizer, batch size, etc. This file is edited and iterated on by the agent.\\n   `program.md` — baseline instructions for one agent. Point your agent here and let it go. This file is edited and iterated on by the human.\\n\\nBy design, training runs for a fixed 5-minute time budget (wall clock, excluding startup/compilation), regardless of the details of your compute. The metric is val_bpb (validation bits per byte) — lower is better, and vocab-size-independent so architectural changes are fairly compared.\\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\\\"a43f90e401148d1f\\\">>>\",\n      \"images\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}"}],"details":{"provider":"tavily","count":1,"tookMs":1365,"externalContent":{"untrusted":true,"source":"web_fetch","provider":"tavily","wrapped":true},"results":[{"url":"https://github.com/karpathy/autoresearch","rawContent":"\n<<<EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a43f90e401148d1f\">>>\nSource: Web Fetch\n---\n## Project structure\n\n\ntrain.py        — model, optimizer, training loop (agent modifies this)\nprogram.md      — agent instructions\npyproject.toml  — dependencies\n```\n\n## Design choices\n\n. Second, this means that autoresearch will find the most optimal model for your platform in that time budget. The downside is that your runs (and results) become not comparable to other people running on other compute platforms.\n   Self-contained. No external dependencies beyond PyTorch and a few small packages. No distributed training, no complex configs. One GPU, one file, one metric.\n\n## Platform support [...] If you are new to neural networks, this \"Dummy's Guide\" looks pretty good for a lot more context.\n\n## Quick start\n\n, Python 3.10+, uv.\n\nundefinedshell\n# 1. Install uv project manager (if you don't already have it)\ncurl -LsSf  | sh\n\n# 2. Install dependencies\nuv sync\n\n# 3. Download data and train tokenizer (one-time, ~2 min)\nuv run prepare.py\n\n# 4. Manually run a single training experiment (~5 min)\nuv run train.py\nundefined\n\nIf the above commands all work ok, your setup is working and you can go into autonomous research mode.\n\n## Running the agent\n\n, then you can prompt something like:\n\n```\nHi have a look at program.md and let's kick off a new experiment! let's do the setup first.\n```\n\nThe `program.md` file is essentially a super lightweight \"skill\".\n\n## Project structure [...] ## How it works\n\n, and runtime utilities (dataloader, evaluation). Not modified.\n   `train.py` — the single file the agent edits. Contains the full GPT model, optimizer (Muon + AdamW), and training loop. Everything is fair game: architecture, hyperparameters, optimizer, batch size, etc. This file is edited and iterated on by the agent.\n   `program.md` — baseline instructions for one agent. Point your agent here and let it go. This file is edited and iterated on by the human.\n\nBy design, training runs for a fixed 5-minute time budget (wall clock, excluding startup/compilation), regardless of the details of your compute. The metric is val_bpb (validation bits per byte) — lower is better, and vocab-size-independent so architectural changes are fairly compared.\n<<<END_EXTERNAL_UNTRUSTED_CONTENT id=\"a43f90e401148d1f\">>>","images":[]}]},"isError":false,"timestamp":1775478322850}}
{"type":"message","id":"feaef5c8","parentId":"5eebbd6c","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:25:53.595Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand autoresearch better. The key insight is:\n\n1. **`train.py`** - the only thing the agent can modify. It's a single file containing the complete training logic (model, optimizer, training loop). The agent edits this file.\n\n2. **`program.md`** - human-written instructions for the agent. The human edits this to guide what the agent should try.\n\n3. **How it works**: The agent reads `program.md` for instructions, modifies `train.py`, runs the experiment, reads the results, decides whether to keep the changes, and iterates.\n\nThe key design principle: **one agent, one objective metric, one file to edit**.\n\n\nFor the user's investment research system, I'm starting to see how this could work, but the analogy breaks down—autoresearch relies on a well-defined metric like validation loss that training can optimize, whereas trading systems face noisy, non-stationary markets where the best metric isn't clear and the system itself is more complex than a single file.\n\nThe more practical approach is to apply the core principles: define a single clear objective, keep the code modular, and maintain an audit trail. I could implement this by establishing a research brief that sets goals, creating a strategy file the agent can modify, running backtests to measure performance, and letting the system iterate through parameter adjustments. The immediate priority is running a proper walk-forward validation with statistical testing to compare against the baseline, then setting up an automated pipeline that explores parameter space and ranks improvements.\n\nBut before diving into implementation, I should understand what the user actually wants—do they want me to adopt this research methodology for the investment system, or are they looking to build something similar for trading? And looking at the interactive card they're referencing, it seems they're asking whether this autoresearch concept is something we should be doing.\n\nI think the most practical path forward is to set up a basic automated research loop using existing tools: define a research objective in a file, let an agent explore strategy parameters through backtests, and then evaluate whether the results justify moving from paper trading to live. Let me outline this approach clearly and ask for their direction on which aspect to prioritize.","thinkingSignature":"a5234b751b09bceefbfedd237c86ea220af0435f7d1e41cf3541fa04c2698574"},{"type":"text","text":"读完了。说一下我的判断：\n\n**autoresearch 的核心设计原则：**\n- 目标明确：验证 loss 下降（客观、无争议）\n- Agent 只改一个文件（`train.py`）\n- 每次实验 5 分钟，有明确的量化反馈\n- 人类写 `program.md` 引导方向\n\n**套到投研系统上的关键问题：**\n\n| autoresearch | 量化策略 |\n|---|---|\n| 验证 loss 下降 | Sharpe/回撤有噪声，不稳定 |\n| 5分钟/次实验 | 一轮 walk-forward 可能要几小时 |\n| 目标无争议 | 策略好坏有运气成分，很难判断是策略强还是随机 |\n| 模型代码可控 | 市场本身在变化，历史规律不一定未来有效 |\n\n---\n\n**结论：autoresearch 的精神有用，直接照搬不现实。**\n\n真正值得借鉴的是**把研究目标写成 `program.md`，让 AI 自主探索、验证、决策**。对你的系统，我能做的具体方向：\n\n**方向 A（立即可做）：参数自动巡检**\n每周自动跑 walk-forward，AI 判断是否需要触发\"重新搜索\"告警——这个今天已经搭好了。\n\n**方向 B（更深入）：策略假设自动生成**\n让 AI 读你所有的研报、因子代码、实验记录，自动生成新的策略假设写到 `research/hypothesis/program.md`，下一个 walk-forward 验证。\n\n**方向 C（复杂但有价值）：把你的持仓决策链路写成 `train.py`**\n让 AI 审计买卖逻辑，发现漏洞，生成改进建议。\n\n---\n\n你现在最想往哪个方向走？我先做方向 A 的收尾，然后确认下周六的巡检 cron 正常运行。"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":106572,"output":785,"cacheRead":21467,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":128824,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775478322870,"responseId":"0622d933903da6727b477d5ddf8ff045"}}
{"type":"message","id":"0ae88f58","parentId":"feaef5c8","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:27:12.402Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b520e273cb4a0c35b251e7b2e99f\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"sender\": \"张玲\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-04-06 20:27 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"张玲 (ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"name\": \"张玲\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b520e273cb4a0c35b251e7b2e99f]\n张玲: abc都想要"}],"timestamp":1775478432396}}
{"type":"message","id":"50e8af1e","parentId":"0ae88f58","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:27:40.986Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants all three directions - A, B, and C. This is a significant scope. Let me think about what's realistic and how to prioritize.\n\nA: Parameter auto audit - already done, just needs confirmation\nB: Strategy hypothesis auto generation - moderate complexity\nC: Portfolio decision chain audit - complex, ongoing\n\nI should be honest about what can be done quickly vs what takes more time, and propose a concrete execution plan. Given the autoresearch spirit, I should focus on building an automated research loop.\n\nLet me think about what I can realistically build:\n\nA: Already built - just verify it's working\nB: Create a pipeline that:\n   1. Reads recent research reports, factor code, experiment results\n   2. Uses an AI to generate new strategy hypotheses\n   3. Writes them to a hypothesis file\n   4. Next walk-forward validates them\n\nC: More complex - would need to:\n   1. Audit the current live trading decision logic\n   2. Identify gaps\n   3. Generate improvements\n\nGiven the user's enthusiasm and desire for all three, I should:\n1. Acknowledge the scope\n2. Propose a phased approach starting with quick wins\n3. Start building B since it's the most valuable and hasn't been done yet\n4. Keep C as ongoing work\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The user said \"abc都想要\" (all three). This is ambitious. Let me propose a concrete plan.\n\nFor the autoreview loop concept (inspired by autoreview):\n- A: Weekly parameter monitoring (already done, just needs to be confirmed working)\n- B: Periodic (e.g., monthly) hypothesis generation based on reading research reports, backtest results, market observations\n- C: Code-level audit of the decision pipeline\n\nI should be honest that C is the most complex and time-intensive, while A is essentially done. B is doable but needs careful design. Let me propose starting with A's confirmation, then B's design, then C as a longer-term project. I need to understand the current decision pipeline first before tackling the code audit, so let me outline a concrete phased approach that balances quick wins with the deeper work.","thinkingSignature":"f5ca4171ebb311bcf9ef2de44bc1d978ebbb0d5cf9af2440f22bd82a06d51a10"},{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] 有野心，我喜欢。说说我的执行计划：\n\n---\n\n**A（立即完成）：参数巡检**\n✅ 已在跑，周六 10:00 自动触发。有告警才推，无告警静默。确认一下：刚才那条测试推送收到了没？\n\n---\n\n**B（本周内）：策略假设自动生成**\n\n设计思路——每月跑一次，AI 读取：\n- 近期 walk-forward 结果（哪些窗口失败了）\n- 持仓异动记录（哪只股票突然涨跌）\n- 研报/新闻情绪（市场在炒什么概念）\n- experiment_registry 里所有策略的\"死因分析\"\n\n然后生成 3~5 条新策略假设，写到 `research/hypothesis/candidate_vX.md`，下一轮 walk-forward 验证。\n\n这个我现在就能开始设计。\n\n---\n\n**C（持续进行）：决策链路审计**\n\n这个最复杂，需要先摸清楚你现在的实盘决策链路到底长什么样。我先问几个问题：\n\n1. **实盘下单前**，信号是怎么生成的？Qlib 跑模型 → 排序 → breadth 过滤 → 人工确认 → 下单？\n2. **有没有人工干预点**？还是在满足条件时自动执行？\n3. **现在跑的是哪套代码**？`qlib_breadth_long_b_v1` 对应的执行脚本是哪个？\n\n把 C 当成一个长期的\"慢慢啃\"项目来做，每次我审计代码时顺手改进，不追求一次搞定。\n\n---\n\n**我的建议执行顺序：A收尾 → B设计 → C逐步推进**\n\n现在先把 A 确认了，然后开始设计 B？"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":74,"output":782,"cacheRead":126939,"cacheWrite":1691,"totalTokens":129486,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1775478432400,"responseId":"0622d9a1439f384112390b4353f14592"}}
{"type":"message","id":"c746e81b","parentId":"50e8af1e","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:30:17.929Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Conversation info (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"message_id\": \"om_x100b520e3b4118a8c3b38a89a027572\",\n  \"sender_id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"sender\": \"张玲\",\n  \"timestamp\": \"Mon 2026-04-06 20:30 GMT+8\"\n}\n```\n\nSender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"张玲 (ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae)\",\n  \"id\": \"ou_47c21eede907b0c4f9fd4d34519d84ae\",\n  \"name\": \"张玲\"\n}\n```\n\n[message_id: om_x100b520e3b4118a8c3b38a89a027572]\n张玲: 我已经收到了你推送的测试消息。现在开始设计b，但是以月为周期我觉得有点太长了，以周为周期吧"}],"timestamp":1775478617923}}
{"type":"message","id":"3926de23","parentId":"c746e81b","timestamp":"2026-04-06T12:30:41.730Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants to design B with a weekly cycle instead of monthly. Let me design the weekly strategy hypothesis generation system.\n\nKey components:\n1. Weekly execution - let's say every Sunday evening or Saturday after the param audit\n2. Data inputs: recent walk-forward results, holdings performance, news/market sentiment, experiment registry\n3. Output: 3-5 new strategy hypotheses written to `research/hypothesis/candidate_vX.md`\n\nLet me design this properly.\n\nThe inputs the AI would read:\n- Recent walk-forward results (last 1-2 weeks)\n- Paper trading performance\n- Real trading journal (if available)\n\n\n- Market breadth data recent trends\n- News/sentiment data\n- Experiment registry failures\n\nI need to figure out where this weekly job should run - I could use the same Saturday 10am param audit slot, but that would mix the two tasks together. It makes more sense to run the hypothesis generation earlier in the week, maybe Wednesday or Thursday, so there's time to review before the weekend. The natural choice would be Sunday evening or Monday morning, giving me the whole week's data to work with. For the file structure, I'm thinking `research/hypothesis/candidate_vX.md` with a JSON registry to track them all. Let me map out the specific files I need to read and write, starting with the most recent walk-forward summary and working back through the week's data.\n\nFor timing, Saturday at 4pm or 8pm makes the most sense—that gives me the full week's data to analyze while still leaving time to prepare before Monday's trading. I'll call it the \"Weekly Research Hypothesis Generation\" and design it to read recent performance data, market breadth trends, paper trading results, and any flagged anomalies, then output a structured hypothesis document that feeds into the next cycle's validation.\n\nNow I'm going to build this out: create the Python script that generates the report, set up a shell wrapper to execute it, and configure a cron job to run it every Saturday at 4pm Shanghai time.","thinkingSignature":"c5cb5397aef15725b11b5c4dd234ec95259f4e074fdce2ec7e5994ef511cb6e7"},{"type":"text","text":"好，先设计 B。确认 A 收到了 ✅\n\n现在开始设计**周度策略假设自动生成系统**：\n\n**执行时间**：每周六 16:00（盘后数据都更新完了，有完整一周的数据可以分析）\n\n**AI 读取内容**：\n- 本周 walk-forward 结果（最近 1-2 个窗口）\n- 本周模拟盘表现（paper profiles）\n- 本周市场宽度变化趋势\n- experiment_registry 里近期失败的策略\"死因\"\n- 本周持仓异动记录（如果有）\n\n**输出**：3~5 条新策略假设，写入 `research/hypothesis/YYYYMMDD_candidates.md`，供下周一人工确认是否加入验证队列\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_yj2cwc9vzqm5_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/paper_*nav*.csv 2>/dev/null | head -5; echo \"---\"; ls /Users/ling/.openclaw/workspace/quant_projects/personal-a-share-research-system/research/reports/ | grep -i \"hypothesis\\|candidate\" | head -10"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":74,"output":660,"cacheRead":21467,"cacheWrite":107094,"totalTokens":129295,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775478617927,"responseId":"0622da5af3a3fc79d638f85a25dd3c2e"}}
